{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_fontaine_ver01/data/sn87055779/00517016688/1927031901/0004.xml":{"full_text":"I\nSOUTH BEND NEWS-TIMES\n_L...\nFHday\u2019i Paid CvcnlaBott\n27,821\nMoraine an4 Evening Edition*.\nVOL. XLIV, NO. 78\nMORNING EDITION\nSOUTH BEND, INDIANA, SATURDAY, MARCH 19, 1927\nEDITOR OF FORD\nPAPER DEFENDS\nCHIEF IN COURT\nBillionaire\u2019s Spokesman Cal\nled as First Witness in\nLibel Hearing.\nMV K. It. HOLMES,\nUnited News Staff Correspondent.\nDDTROIT, March 18.\u2014William\nCameron, official spokesman for the\nworld\u2019s first billionaire, came to the\ndefense of his chief Friday during\nhis direct testimony in Aaron Sa\npiro\u2019s million-dollar libel suit\nagainst Henry Ford,\nAs editor of the billionaire auto\nmobile manufacturer\u2019s Dearborn In\ndependent, which is alleged to have\nlibeled Sapiro through charging that\nhe headed a \u201cband of international\nJetrs,\u201d mulcting American farmers\nof millions of dollars, Cameron was\ncalled by Saplro\u2019s counsel as the\nfirst witness.\nCameron\u2019s testimony was designed\nto show that, although Ford owned\nthe Independent, it was not the\nmouthpiece for all of his ideas re\ngarding war, politics and markets.\n\u201cDid you ever discuss with him\n(Ford) the policies of the paper?\u201d\nCameron was asked.\n\u201cJn a most general way,\u201d the edi\ntor said.\nAsks Many Questions\nBut there were many other ques\ntions about Fordv which Cameron\nwas prevented from answering by\nobjections of U. S.' Sen. James A.\nReed, chief of the Ford attorneys.\nCameron said Ford looks charit\nably upon the soviet government of\nRussia, or more charitably than does\nhis weekly publication.\nAnd, while the Independent may\nstand for preparedness. Ford is\n\u201cstrong against war and all that\npertains to it.\u201d\nNo sooner was Cameron on the\nstand and had disposed of the pre\nliminary questions than the inquisi\ntive William Henry Gallagher, at\ntorney for Aaron Sapiro, wanted to\nknow a lot of things about Ford and\nthe Independent.\nQ.\u2014How are the policies of the\nIndependent shaped? Do you have\nmeetings and conferences of execu\ntives to decide those things?\nA.\u2014Yes.\nDrops In Often\nQ.\u2014And does Mr. Ford come in\nand talk things over with you?\nA.\u2014Yes, he is in t,he habit of drop\nping in quite frequently.\nQ.\u2014Did you ever discuss with him\nthe policies of the paper?\nA.\u2014Well, in a most general way.\nQ.\u2014Well, have you on occasion\ndiffered with Mr. Ford on questions\nof policy?\nA.\u2014Yes.\nQ.\u2014Tell when such differences\narose and what were they about?\nA.\u2014I can\u2019t say just when such\nthings have happened, but\u2014well,\nMr. Ford is strong against war and\nall that pertains to it and the paper\nstands for preparedness. Mr. Ford\nlooks on the Russian soviet govern\nment more leniently than we do.\nQ.\u2014Do you mean he favors the\nsoviet government?.,\nA.\u2014No, he\u2019s just more lenient to\nwards it than the Independent.\nQ.\u2014Did you and Mr. Ford ever\n(Continued on Page 4 Column 1)\nHINT SOLUTION OF\nTANGLE IN MEXICO\nNo Disposition to Seize\nAmerican Property, Says\nState Department.\nBy United News:\nWASHINGTON, March 18.\nVindication of the administration\u2019s\nMexican policy is beginning to ap\npear, according to the view at the\nWhite House.\nThe White House spokesman has\ncalled attention to the fact that the\nMexican government has not seized\nany American property and shows an\nindisposition to do so.\nThis statement, coupled with the\nstate department information earli\ner in the week that there is no\ndanger of a break with Mexico, gave\na hopeful turn to the critical situa\ntion that has existed since the Mexi\ncan oil laws went Into effect Jan. 1.\nSome deduced from these two op\ntimistic expressions that an agree\nment solving the dispute either has\nbeen reached or is imminent. Known\nfacts do not warrant such conclus\nions but the atmosphere decidedly\nhas taken a friendlier turn.\nThis change of tone coincides with\nthe return of Mexican Ambassador\nTellez from Mexico City, where he\nwent recently on a mysterious mis\nsion.\nFLOODS THREATENING\nMISSISSIPPI TOWNS\nBy United Sows:\nMARKS, Miss., March 18. This\ntown virtually was waterbound Fri\nday and Darling, seven miles north,\nreported the highest water since\n1S17 and imminent danger of a seri\nous flood. Convicts under volunteer\nguard were working at the rtver\nlevee.\nMore than 200,000 acres of land\nwas inundated in the valley of the\nColdwater river. Roads in all direc\ntions from Marks were inundated.\nWifleather\nIndiana\u2014Cloudy, with rain In south\nand central portions Saturday and\nprobably Sunday; much colder.\nlower .Michigan Mostly cloudy\nSaturday and Sunday; colder.\nAmericans Reveal\nStrange Ideas on\nC ommandments\nBy MAURICE MERMEY\n(United News Staff Correspondent)\nCHICAGO, March 18. America\ndoesn\u2019t know the 10 commandments,\nat least well enough to recite them,\naccording to the Northwestern\nChristian Advocate, a periodical of\nthe Methodist Episcopal church pub\nlished in Chicago.\nThe Advocate conducted a religi\nous questionnaire, and the results\nwere startling to the Advocate.\n\u201cThere must be no false faces be\nfore me,\u201d an unenlightened Ameri\ncan said was one of the command\nments. \u201cKeep away from your\nneighbor\u2019s wife,\u201d was another which\ncan\u2019t be found in the decalogue.\nAnd the provincials have their\nown ideas on the commandments,\nthe publication found. From one who\nlives in the little town of Buffola,\n111., came the assurance that the 10\ncommandments was a \u201cswell pic\nture.\" A college girl in Sious City,\nla., quoted the beatitudes.\n\u201cIn few instances were the tests\nlimited to Methodists,\u201d the Advocate\nsaid Friday. \u201cMost of the testers\nappear to have gone abroad in their\ncommunities, gleaning in as many\ndifferent religious fields as possible.\nAs far as determined, no one church\nhas accomplished a markedly super\nior sort of religious education.\n\u201cBoys and girls in the Sunday\nschools were found to be letter per\nfect in reciting the 10 command\nments\u2014providing not more than a\nyear had elapsed since they studied\nthem. Otherwise, there was no\nmarked difference among juniors\nand adults, save that the older folk\nwere more embarrassed wrhen the\ntruth dawned on them.\u201d\nSome of the answers follow:\n\u201cYou should not take your neigh\nbor\u2019s cow.\u201d\n\u201cThere is a long one about water\nunder the earth.\u201d\n\u201cThou shalt not murder\u201d (quoted\nby a police magistrate).\n\u201cLove they neighbor as yiyself.\u201d\n\u201cKeep the Sabbath and make it\nholy.\u201d\nTROOPS MOBILIZED\nIN KANSAS AS MOB\nDEMANDS PRISONER\nThousand Infuriated Persons\nStorm Jail Where Negro\nSuspect is Held.\nBy United News:\nCOFFEYVILLE, Kan., March 18.\n\u2014Kansas National Guardsmen have\nbeen mobilized at Independence and\nj will depart for Coffeyville, where a\nmob of 1,000 infuriated persons has\nattacked the city hall and Jail.\nOne negro is being held at the\nI jail, located atop the city hall, in\nI connection with an attack upon two\nhigh school girls Friday morning.\nTwo other Negroes were released\nFriday afternoon after questioning.\nChaos reigns in Coffeyville, the\nlike of which this town has not seen\nsince the Dalton brothers made their\nsensational raid in the 1890\u2019s.\nThe mob smashed windows of the\ncity hall, shots filled the air, auto\nmobiles were running wild. Police\ndefending the Jail threw a tear bomb\nto dispel the crowd, but the men\nand women in the mob demanded\nthe prisoner, Curtis Smith, 30. The\ncrowd expressed its desire to lynch\nhim.\nTroop B of the 117th cavalry Kan\nsas National Guard, has commenced\nmobilization and will soon depart for\nCoffeyville.\nVolleys of shots have been poured\nin the direction of pleading Ne\ngroes, but no casualties have been\nreported.\nNational guards were enroute in\nautomobiles from Yates Center,\nKan., police were notified at 11\no\u2019clock.\nMen were walking tiie streets car\nrying rifles over their shoulders.\nBefore midnight, a hardware store\nhad been entered and gun stocks\nstolen. Three white men were ar\nrested, charged with breaking into\nthe store.\nCars loaded with Negroes dashed\nout of Coffeyville, but the Negroes\nwho remained in town were arming\nthemselves, according to Lieut.\nBraum Bentley of the local cavalry.\n3 \u201cPOEMS OF PASSION\u201d\nPUT IN COURT RECORD\nBy United News:\nOAKLAND, Calif., March IS.\nThree \u201cpoems of passion\u201d which\nwere described as too suggestive for\ncourt reading, have been written in\nto records of a preliminary hearing\nof three members of the \"White\nBrotherhood,\u201d alleged Oakland love\ncult.\nMrs. Erma Gibbs, the \"ermen\ngaarde,\u201d and Russell J. Alley, the\n\u201comar\u201d of mystic cult rites, were\nheld for trial on charges of con\ntributing to the delinquency of Al\nley\u2019s 15-year-old son and Caroline\nMerwin, 17-year-old school girl.\nThe case of Mrs. Gertrude Wright,\n\"zareda\u201d and high priestess of the\norder and alleged author of the sug\ngestive poetry, was continued until\nMonday.\nCAPITAL GIRL WOULD\nDIVORCE SPANIARD\nBy T'nitpcl News:\nWASHINGTON, March 18.\u2014guit\nfor divorce on the grounds that she\nwas wed by force has been filed by\nKatrina Van Rennssalaer, 21-year\no!d Washington society girl, against\nGustavo De Medina, former attache\nof the Spanish embassy.\nMedina also has a wife In Spain,\nthe divorce petition alleges. The girl\nsaid she never lived with the Span\niard after the marriage ceremony.\nCOOLDGE SAYS\nTAXES WILL BE\nCUT NEXT YEAR\nLarge Payments on Incomes\nInsure Slash in 1928,\nPresident Believes.\nBy RAYMOND CLAPPER,\nUnited News Staff Correspondent.\nWASHINGTON, March 18. Tax\nreduction next winter has been defi\nnitely forecast at the White House in\nthe light of heavy income tax pay\nments this week.\nThe White House spokesman an\nnounced today that some tax reduc\ntion is likely. How much and where\nthe cuts 'will be made are questions\nto be determined later.\nAt the suggestian of President\nCoolidge, the House ways and means\ncommittee has arranged to reassem\nble here early next fall, in advance\nof the convening of Congress, to\nprepare a new tax reduction bill. By\nthat time, it is expected that the ex\ntent of the surplus will be known,\nand the business outlook will be\nclearer.\nSurplus Growing.\nSecretary of the Treasury Mellon\nhas estimated that by June 30, the\nsurplus will be half a billion dollars.-!\nMellon still is unwilling to make a\nflat prediction regarding tax reduc\ntion, but the White House oral state\nment reveals definitely the intention\nof the administration. Some of the\nestimated surplus will be due to the\nfact that Congress failed to pass sev\neral appropriation bills, and it is\nexpected that this money will be\nchecked but soon after the new Con\ngress meets.\nProbably the biggest factor in\ndetermining the amount of the next\ntax reduction will be the business\noutlook. Considerable recession had\nbeen expected this year, but business\nhas fallen off \u2019ess than was feared.\nCheck payments for the second week\nof March, for instance, although\nsmaller than the week earlier, were\nlarger than for the corresponding\nweek of 1926. Stock exchange\nprices are above the level of a year\nago. Bond prices are up. Business\nfailures were less numerous the\nsecond week of March than they\nwere the previous week or for the\nsame period a year ago. All of these\nare indications that business is in a\nhealthy condition.\n21U lO lili jt irai,\nThe Importance of the business\nsituation in connection with tax re\nduction is clear in view of the as\nsertion of treasury officials that a\ndrop of 10 per cent in business would\nso seriously cut into tax revenues\nas to wipe out entirely the margin\nbetween government income and\noutgo that comprises the treasury\nsurplus.\nSecretary of the Treasury Mellon\nrecently indicated that if any tax re\nduction is made the automobile tax\nwill be among the first to receive\nconsideration. There is heavy pres\nsure to reduce the corporation tax to\n10 per cent. It was put up to 12\nand one-half in the previous tax bill\nin lieu of the elimination of the\ncapital stock tax. Taxes on admis\nsions, club dues and the stamp tax\nl\u201dv^^o^nuedaon^Page^rColumn^l)\u00b0^\nARKANSAS TORNADO\nFATAL TO ELEVEN\nLatest Report Shows Be\ntween 30 and 40 Persons\nInjured by Storm.\nBy United News:\nBENTON, Ark., March 18.\u2014Lat\nest reports here show that 11 per\nsons were killed and between 30 and\n40 injured in the tornado which\nstruck this county last Thursday.\nOf the injured, six are in a local\nhospital and three of these are se\nriously injured. The dead are: Edgar\nSmith, wife and two children, 7 and\n5: Lennie Gash, Artis Cash, Lonnie\nCash, John M. Buckalew and wife,\nMiss Cora Moody and a youth named\nMcAlister.\nThe storm struck about seven\nmiles southwest of this city, demol\nishing a, number of buildings and\nsweeping a path through the timber\nfor a distance of several miles.\nPISTOL MATCH WINNER\nIS KILLED BY LOSER\nBy United News:\nHARLAN, Ky., March 18.\nAngered because Harry Dugger had\nbeaten him in a pistol target match,\nArthur West is said to have turned\nhis gun on Dugger, and in the en\nsuing struggle, Dugger was shot and\nkilled.\nThe shooting occurred at Lenarue,\nsix miles from here.\n_._\nPORTUGUESE FLYERS\nARRIVE IN BRAZIL\nBy United News:\nPORT NATAL, Brazil, March 18.,\n\u2014Sarmento Beires and his compan- 1\nIon Portuguese flyers In the sea\nplane Argos have arrived from the\nisland of Fernando De Noronha.\nThey alighted off the coast of\nFernando De Noronha Thursday aft\ner a flight across the south Atlantic j\nfrcm the BIssangos Archipelago, off\nPortuguese West Africa.\nINDIANA IS GIVEN\nWARNING OF FLOOD\nBy United News:\nWASHINGTON, March 18.\u2014The\nweather bureau tonight issued the\nfollowing flood warnings: Green\nriver of Kentucky and the Ohio\nriver from Evansville, Ind., to\nCairo, 111., with a stable between 48.6\nand 49 feet at Cairo by March 98.\nOver Sunday Tourists\nBy\nHall\na\nNEVADA MAKES NEW\nBID FOR NATION\u2019S\nDIVORCE BUSINESS\nLegislature Reduces Resid\nence Requirement to\nMeet Competition.\nBy United News:\nCARSON CITY, Nev., March 18.\u2014\nOnly three months residence in Ne\nvada is required befqre a person may\napply for a divorce.\nThe state legislature Friday passed\na bill, changing the residence re\nquirement from six to three months,\nand the governor signed it.\nAs a resutj, this state, long known\nas the divorce center of the country,\nis expected to see a fresh impetus\nof this kind of business.\nThe bill also carries a provision\nmaking insanity a ground for com\nplaint in a divorce action.\nReading Industry\nThe divorce business has been one\nof Reno\u2019s chief industries and, until\na few 'years ago, Reno\u2019s divorce\n\u201ccrop\u201d totalled more than 1,200\nwealthy easterners annually. That\nmeant a yearly revenue of $1,500,\n000.\nBusiness was getting better every\nyear, until Paris came to the front as\na divorce mecca. The French city\nseemed to appeal more to persons\nanxious to forget marital blunders\nthan did the bleak desert country of\nNevada.\nThen some one in Hollywood\nstarted a craze for divorces In Mexi\nco, and Reno was further gnawed\nby envy.\nonly 7ou .Divorces\nLast year, Reno felt the pinch of\ndivorce competition more than ever.\nOnly 750 divorces were granted, and\nthe city\u2019s revenue volplaned below\nthe $1,000,000 mark.\nWyoming threatened to pass a 90\nday law to steal what divorce pres\ntige Reno had left. There were\nwhsiperings that Florida was consid\nering similar action.\nThere is only one flaw In the law\nwhich will make Nevada the easiest\nstate in the union in which to obtain\na divorce. Reno merchants com\nplain that divorce seekers will do\nonly three months\u2019 business with\nthem instead of six. But they find\nsome ground for solace in the belief\nthat divorce cases now will flourish\nto such an extent that the volume\nwill make up for shorter individual\nstays in the city.\nWill Rogers Say*\u2014\nEDITOR NEWS-TIMES:*\nPOCATELLO, Idaho, March 18.\n\u2014It took me 48 states to do it,\nbut; I finally arrived in one where\nevery one knows who one of their\nsenators Is. I go to Borah\u2019s home\ntown tomorrow. I want to see\nthis place before it is made a\nshrine for honoring the only man\nin public life in his time with in\ndependent thought, when every\nbody else\u2019s ideas are as standard\nized as Ford parts. What\u2019s best\nfor the political machine is best\nfor the politician. What\u2019s best\nfor America is best for Borah.\nAsk Mr. Coolidge how far wrong\nI am.\nWILL.\nWIFE GETS DIVORCE\nBECAUSE HUBBY HAS\nIRRESISTIBLE EYES\nBy United News:\nDES MOINES, la., March 18.\u2014\nHe had \u201cbaby blue eyes which\nwomen couldn\u2019t resist,\u201d Mrs. Alice\nGreen claimed in asking for a di\nvorce from husband No. 4. He\nalso broke a plate over her head\nand hurled a cake at her, she\nsaid. James Green asserted that\nhis wife \u201cwore the pants in our\nfamily and once she knocked me\ndown stairs and another time\nthrew me into ditch.\u201d\nMrs. Green was granted a di\nvorce.\nSOLON OWNS BOOZE,\nNEWSPAPER STATES\nHijacked Liquor Belonged\nto U. S. Senator, Says\nWashington. News.\nBy United News:\nWASHINGTON, March 18.\u2014Pre\nwar liquor, hijacked last week from\na transfer truck in Maryland and\nsubsequently turned over to Wash\nington police, was property of a\nUnited States senator, the Washing\nton News, a Scripps-Howard news\npaper, says.\nThis senator is influential in Dis\ntrict of Columbia affairs, which ac\ncounts for the secrecy thrown over\nthe affair by police, .the News de\nclares.\nSecretary of the Treasury Mellon\nstated at a recent press conference\nhe knew the owner of the liquor and\nthat the transfer was legal as a per\nmit for its removal had been issued.\nHowever, the secretary refused to\ndivulge his name.\nSeven cases of the pre-war stuff\nwere being brought from Bryn\nMawr, Pennsylvania, last week.\nWhile the truck crew .was lunching,\naccording to their story, the truck\nwas stolen, robbed of its cargo and\nburned.\nTwo nights later, a truck was\nbacked up to a Washington police\nstation and the liquor which had\nbeen stolen was unloaded.\n\u201cThe senator to whom the liquor\nbelonged is active socially, and is\nnoted'among the elect for the elab\norateness of his entertainments and\nthe high quality of liquor which he\nserves,\u201d the News says.\nEX-CHAMP\u2019S SISTER\nIS INJURED IN FALL\nBy United News\nLOS ANGELES. March 18.\u2014While\npeeling an orange, Mrs. John Demp\nsey, sisteV-ln-law of the former\nheavyweight boxing champion, clip\nped and fell on a knife, suffering a\npainful wound in the chest. Physi\ncian said the wound was not serious.\nCHARLES G. DAWES\nSAILS FOR PANAMA\nBy United News:\nHAVANA, March 18.\u2014Vice Pres\nident Charles G. Dawes, with his\nfamily and the party of friends ac\ncompanying him .sailed Friday night\non the United Fruit steamer Toioa\nfor Panama.\nDawes spent the day quietly, going\nto the palace to bid good-bye to\nPresident Machado.\nDEARTH DEMANDS\nEARLY HEARING\nON OUSTER SUIT\nSenate Trial of Case Sche\nduled to Open Monday\nMorning.\nBy United Press:\nINDIANAPOLIS, March 18.\u2014\nFrederick Van Nuys, attorney for\nJudge Clarence Dearth of Muncie,\nplanned today to seek Immediate\nhearing on the Dearth ouster suit In\nthe Marion county Circuit court.\nThe suit seeks a writ of mandamus\nto compel Gov. Jackson to appoint\na successor to Dearth while the Mun\ncie judge is under impeachment\ncharges before the senate.\nVan Nuys explained that-with the\nsenate hearing on the Dearth case\nscheduled to open Monday after\nnoon he was anxious to get the man\ndamus hearing out of the ^jay before\nthat time.\nDemurrers to the mandamus pe\ntition have been filed by Atty. Gen.\nGilliom for the governor and by Van\nNuys for Dearth.\nPlans for the defense were out\nlined yesterday at a conference be\ntween Dearth and Van Nuys here.\nAfter the conference Van Nuys an\nnounced Judge Dearth would testify\nin the senate hearing.\nTwo hundred and fifty witnesses\nare to be called to testify for Judge\nDearth, Van Nuys said.\nAt the outset of the senate trial\nJudge Dearth will file a motion to\ndismiss the charges, contending the\nhouse of representatives stepped be\nyond its constitutional powers when\nit impeached him.\n\nNEGRO PASTOR FILES\nSUIT FOR $1,000 BET\nBy United News:\nBALTIMORE, Md., March 18.\u2014\nWilliam Mclvy, Negro Methodist\npreacher, today sued in City court to\ncollect from M. S. -Bansfield, Negro\nSeventh Day Adventist, $1,000,\nwagered on which day of the week is\nthe Sabbath.\nMclvy claims that he and Bans\nfield debated before a Negro audi\nence of 700. By a vote of 600 to\n100, the congregation decided in\nfavor of Sunday. Bansfield said that\naudience was composed of 600\nMethodists and 100 Seventh Day\nAdventists. Besides, said Bansfield,\n\u201cI didn\u2019t promise him $1,000 if he\nwon the debate. I only told him\nI\u2019d like to see him get it.\u201d\nDeb Is Coming!\nShe\u2019ll be here Monday. Deb\nis the Gloria Swanson of the\ncomic strips. Style, dash, chic are\nall hers. She is a girl men can\u2019t\nforget. Pretty, young, bright\neager for adventure, watching life\nthrough the rose colored glasses\nof youth. Her life is set against\nhuman, colorful background of\nreal people\u2014from her boss whose\ndisposition depends upon the\nchecks in the day\u2019s mail, to the\nballoon-pantied boys she meets at\nthe supper clubs. Starting next\nMonday Debs will be with us daily\nexcept Sunday and she\u2019ll hit you\nright square on the funny bone.\nWatch for her.\nReserve Supplies\nWill Tide Nation\nOver Coal Strike\nBY ALFRED P. RECK,\nUnited News Staff Correspondent.\nCopyright, 1927, By United News.\nWASHINGTON, March 18.\u2014Con\nsumers will have plenty of coal re\ngardless of the threatened walkout\nof union miners in bituminous\nfields, officials of the bureau of\nmines inform the United News.\nAs far as the individual consumer\nis concerned, except for a possible\nslight increase in price, the effects\nof a walkout would be negligible,\nthey declare.\nAmerica\u2019s soft coal consumption\nfrom April 1 until cold weather sets\nin is approximately 8,000,000 tons\nweekly.\nThis amount can be produced by\nnon-union mines and in fields where\nagreements for continued operation\nhave been reached, according to the\nbureau.\nHuge Surplus\nBy April 1, surplus stocks of bitu\nminous coal will total between 60,\n000,000 and 80,000,000 tons, it is\nestimated. The last survey by the\nbureau of mines, on Jan. 1, dis\nclosed 55,000,000 tons on hand.\nIf the strike does come, the bu\nreau pointed out, the only incon\nvenience will be in rerouting coal\nshipments.\nThe warm summer months would\nnot touch the reserve supplies of\ncoal, so they could be held until fall\nto be used if necessary, officials de\nclared.\nYards Stocked\nBy fall, the average consumption\nof coal increases 2,000,000 tons\nweekly and, with huge stocks on\nhand, the country would be able to\ndrift through the winter and still\nhave some reserve left.\nPublic utilities, industries and\nrailroads have been stocking their\nstorage yards until they are pre\npared to withstand a seige of\nmonths, should the occasion demand.\nDepartment of labor officials, with\na keen eye on the situation, see no\ncause for alarm.\nPossibilities of a general strike\nare vague, the labor department\nsays, expressing hope that differ\nences between miners and operators\nwill be straightened out before the\nexpiration of the Jacksonville wage\nscale agreement on April 1.\nTemporary Settlement*\nTemporary settlements have been\nreached in central Pennsylvania,\nWashington, Wyoming and Montana,\nwith conferences under way in Iowa,\nMissouri, Arkansas, Indiana and\nKansas, it is pointed out.\nAlthough the Miami conference\nbetween coal operators and repre\nsentatives of the United' Mine Work\ners union ended in a deadlock, union\nofficials will not object to district\nagreements in which there is no re\nduction in the present wage scale,\nlabor department officials empha\nsised.\nConsumation of district agree\nments in Indiana, Iowa and the\nsouthwest region would limit the\nscope of the threatened strike until\nnot more than 150,000 miners, at\nthe maximum, would be affected.\nAt the labor department it is \"no\ncause for a strike alarm\u201d and at the\nbureau of mines it\u2019s \u201cno cause for\nalarm even if there is a cause for a\nj strike alarm.\u201d\nNEW ESCAPE PLOT\nAT JOLIET FOILED\nSaw and Two Steel Bars\nSharpened for Daggers\nAre Found in Cell.\nJOLIET, 111., March 18.\u2014Another\nattempted Joliet jailbreak \u2022was\nfoiled Friday.\nA steel cutting saw and two steel\nbars filed to sharp points\u2014to be\nused as daggers\u2014were found in\npossession of Charles Duschowskl,\none of the six doomed convicts who\nwere three times given stays of exe\ncution.\nSheriff Albert Markgraf, State\u2019s\nAttorney Hjalmar Rehn and two\nother officials went to the cells hous\ning Duschowskl, Walter Stalesky\nand Charles Shader, the three Amer\nicans who did not escape a week ago\nwhen their three Mexican compan\nions dashed to liberty.\nThe officials ordered them to stick\ntheir hands through the cells\u2019 cross\nbars to be handcuffed while they\nmade a search. Difschowski was\nthe only one who objected. He was\noverpowered by guards. The saw\nwas found in his trousers and the\nsharpened bare, broken from a cot,\nalso were found.\nCOLORADO CITY HIT\nBY SPRING BLIZZARD\nBy T.\u2019nited News:\nDENVER, Colo., March 18.\u2014Den\nver was caught in the grip of a blix\nzard late Friday.\nCarried abreast of a high wind,\nthe storm swept down from the\nmountain slopes early in the after\nnoon with Intensity increasing\nhourly.\nAt first, the snc v melted as rapid\nly as it fell. Then came a lowering\nof temperature, and, within one\nhour, more than an inch of snow\ncovered the, ground and began to\ndrift.\n10 PERSONS DIE IN\nBUST ON OIL BOAT\nBy United News:\nRIO DE JANEIRO, March .18.\u2014\nTen peneons have been killed in an\nexplosion on the Marte, a Standard\n011 boat anchored at Rio Orande Da\nSul, Brazil, according to a dispatch\nto the newspaper A Nolte.\nThe explosion occurred in a cargo\nof gasoline. The captain, his wife,\nsix children and two members of the\ncrew were killed.\nOFFICIAL THINK\n1927WILLSHOW\nLARGER PROFITS\nContinued Prosperity for\nCity Seems Assured by\nEncouraging Report.\nAdded evidence that South Bend\nwill continue to prosper during 1927\nwas given Friday afternoon in the\nannual report of the Bendix Brake\nCo., one of the city\u2019s youngest and\nlustiest industries.\nComing at the end of a four-week\nperiod filled -with indications of\nprosperity, the Bendix report an\nnounced earnings for 1926 of\n$413,000, or $6.36 a share. This is\nalmost double the earnings per share\nlast year.\nIn publishing the report, company\nofficials expressed hope that the net\nearnings in 1927 would be almost T^<\nthree times as great, and would\namount to about $1,300,000.\nThe Bendix report shows that the\ncompany is keeping pace with the\nprosperity of other industries, and\nof the city at large.\nA month ago, one new theater was\nopened; one was re-opened, and\nplans for the construction of an\nother new playhouse were an\nnounced.\nProgress is being made on the\nconstruction of a huge coliseum for\nthe city.\nStuclebaker snows ouin.\nA few weeks ago the Studebaker\ncorporation announced a production\nrate of a car a minute. The March\nproduction schedule of the Stude-\nbaker plant calls for 17,000 cars, an\nincrease of 5,000 over February pro*\nduction. About 12,000 employes are\nbusy at the Studebaker plant.\nOnly a few days ago, a new pro\nject was announced. This Is the\nconstruction of a $1,000,000 hotel on\nthe site of the plant of the South\nBend Woolen Mills.\nThe report of the Bendix Brake\nCo. was received here over the\nprivate wires of E. Lowitz Co.,\nbrokers.\nIt quoted officials of the company\nas confident that earnings for the\nfirst quarter of 1927 would be ample\nto cover all dividend requirements 0\nfor the entire year. This would\nleave earnings for the remaining jo\nnine months as surplus. '\"'I\nAddition Being Built.\nExpansion of the plant of the i\nBendix Brake Co., on the western\ncity limits, is now in progress. When\nthe work has been completed, the\nproduction facilities of the plant will\nbe almost doubled.\nThe Bendix brake is being used\nmore and more generally as standard\nequipment on automobiles, and pro\nduction at the plant has been speed\ned up accordingly.\nA change in the dividend rate\nwas not discussed at the meeting.\nHORSE WHIPPING CASE\nTO GET COURT AIRING\nBy United News:\nLOS ANGELES, March 18,\u2014De\ntails of an. alleged horse whipping\nadministered by J. Stuart Blacktop,\nmotion picture director, to Lieut.\nGerard De Merveaux, fencing mas\nter, will be aired in court here Mon\nday.\nBlackton charges that De Mer\nveaux struck and attacked Mrs.\nBlackton in her home in April, 1925.\nA subsequent slander suit for $250,\n000, Hied by De Merveaux still is\npending in the courts.\n\u201cDRYER WOMEN\u201d, ASKS\nW. C. T. U. PRESIDENT\nBy United News:\nDES MOINES, la., March 18.\u2014\nSpeaking at the annual state con\nvention of the Iowa League of\nWomen Voters, Mrs. Ida B. Wise\nSmith, state president of the W. C.\nT. U. made a plea for \"better women\ncandidates for public office.\u201d\n\"We are ashamed,\u201d she said, \u201cof\nthe three women we have in Con\ngress. I have seen them vote wet\nagain and again and once they voted\ncontrary to our plans for good mov\ning pictures,\u201d Mrs. Wise Smith said.\nCANTONESE FORCES\nMARCH ON SHANGHAI\nBy United News:\nSHANGHAI. March 19.\u2014(Satur\nday)\u2014Pressure against Shanghai\nfrom the south, has been resumed by\nthe armies of Canton.\nShanghai is faced with two ad\nvancing Cantonese armies, one with\nin 20 miles of its gates and the oth\ner, further inland, 60 miles away.\nA Practice\nInstrument?\nThe Classified Want Ad bargain\ncolumns sparkle with excellent\nused musical Instrument offers.\nA practice piano or a fine one\u2014\nslightly used or really \"second\nhand?\" The place to find it and\nyou can Invariably buy for a small\ndown payment, la in the \u201cmighty\nmites\" on the Classified pages.\nThey are the peoples' market\nplace. A three-line ad reaches\n125,000 and coats but SO cents.","height":"32104","width":"24656"}}
